<BIOGRAPHY SEX="FEMALE" PERSON="BRWWRITER"><ORLANDOHEADER TYPE="text"><FILEDESC><TITLESTMT><DOCTITLE>Lady Lucy Herbert : biography</DOCTITLE></TITLESTMT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><AUTHORITY>Orlando Project</AUTHORITY></PUBLICATIONSTMT><SOURCEDESC>Created from original research by members of the Orlando Project</SOURCEDESC></FILEDESC><REVISIONDESC><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="SUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>18 October 2011</DATE><ITEM>Initial document given to tagger.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>2 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>3 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>4 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>7 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>9 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>14 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>14 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>15 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>17 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>17 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>17 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RBV" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>17 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>18 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>22 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>22 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>23 November 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft c, rbv p</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>24 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="PUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>28 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>16 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>cfb, cft c pilot43</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="PUB" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>16 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub c pilot43</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY WORKSTATUS="REV" RESP="MKD" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>19 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY></REVISIONDESC></ORLANDOHEADER><DIV0><HEADING>Biography</HEADING><STANDARD>Herbert, Lady Lucy</STANDARD><DIV1><PERSONNAME><DIV2><DATASTRUCT><DATAITEM><BIRTHNAME WROTEORPUBLISHEDAS="WROTEPUBLISHEDASYES" REG="Herbert, Lady Lucy"><GIVEN>Lucy</GIVEN><SURNAME>Herbert</SURNAME></BIRTHNAME></DATAITEM><DATAITEM><STYLED WROTEORPUBLISHEDAS="WROTEPUBLISHEDASYES" REG="Herbert, Lady Lucy">Lady</STYLED></DATAITEM><DATAITEM><RELIGIOUSNAME REG="Teresa Joseph, Sister">Sister Teresa (or Theresa) Joseph</RELIGIOUSNAME><RELIGIOUSNAME REG="Teresa Joseph, Mother">Mother Teresa Joseph</RELIGIOUSNAME></DATAITEM></DATASTRUCT></DIV2></PERSONNAME></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Birth and Family</HEADING><BIRTH><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="SYS"><DATE VALUE="1669-03-25" CERTAINTY="BY">1668 or 1669</DATE><CHRONPROSE><BIRTHPOSITION>LLH was born at the fortified stronghold of <PLACE><PLACENAME>Powis Castle</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="Welshpool"></SETTLEMENT> in <REGION CURRENT="Powys" REG="Montgomeryshire">Montgomeryshire</REGION><GEOG REG="Wales"></GEOG></PLACE>, the youngest but one of a large and distinguished <ORGNAME STANDARD="Roman Catholic Church">Roman Catholic</ORGNAME> family.</BIRTHPOSITION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Tayler 6" DBREF="70086">6</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Lady Lucy Herbert" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P><NAME>Henrietta Tayler</NAME> gives the year of her birth as 1668; the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Oxford Dictionary of National Biography</TITLE> gives it as 1669. Under the old-style calendar the months now dated January to March 1669 would have formed part of 1668.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Tayler 6" DBREF="70086">6</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Lady Lucy Herbert" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SCHOLARNOTE></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><BIRTHPOSITION>Her siblings were a brother and four sisters, all but her sister Winifred older than she was.</BIRTHPOSITION><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Taylor, Family Tree" DBREF="70086">Family Tree</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></BIRTH></DIV1><DIV1><CULTURALFORMATION><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Her family&apos;s <CLASS SOCIALRANK="NOBILITY" SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES">titles, wealth, elite status</CLASS>, and remarkable record of high ability were somewhat offset by the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Roman Catholic Church"><DENOMINATION SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" REG="Roman Catholic">Roman Catholic</DENOMINATION></ORGNAME> faith which excluded them from some of the civil rights and privileges possessed by other <NATIONALITY SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" REG="English">English</NATIONALITY> or <NATIONALITY SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" REG="Welsh">Welsh</NATIONALITY> subjects. Their loyalty to the <POLITICALAFFILIATION MEMBERSHIP="MEMBERSHIPYES" REG="monarchist">monarchy</POLITICALAFFILIATION>, which had put them on the losing side in the <TOPIC>English Civil War</TOPIC>, caused the forfeit of a large part of their estates. At the time of Lucy&apos;s birth in the reign of <NAME STANDARD="Charles II, King">Charles II</NAME>, Catholics were tolerated, but while she was growing up they were repeatedly persecuted on suspicion of plots to overthrow the government. They enjoyed power and influence during the brief reign of <NAME STANDARD="James II, King">James II</NAME>, but when James was ousted the Herbert family, like many others, became exiles for their religious and political allegiances.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (c.1626-1696)" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></CULTURALFORMATION></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>LLH grew up mostly at <PLACE><PLACENAME>Powis Castle</PLACENAME>, near <SETTLEMENT>Welshpool</SETTLEMENT> in <REGION CURRENT="Powys" REG="Montgomeryshire">Montgomeryshire</REGION><GEOG REG="Wales"></GEOG></PLACE> (the present Powys), a medieval fortress on a steep ridge, built of pink stone and sometimes called Redcastle.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Lady Lucy Herbert and Percy Herbert" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="National Trust" DBREF="70587"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> This came into the hands of the Herbert family in 1578 after playing a centuries-long role in fighting between Welsh and English warlords. It was taken by force as late as 1644, during the <TOPIC>English Civil War</TOPIC>. Repairs and rebuilding, with the construction of the unique terraced gardens, began after the Restoration and no doubt lasted through Lady Lucy&apos;s youth. Her family also owned a grand townhouse in <PLACE><PLACENAME>Lincoln&apos;s Inn Fields</PLACENAME>, <SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (c.1626-1696) and William Herbert (1657x61-1745)" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><VIOLENCE><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN1="NATIONALINTERNATIONAL1" RELEVANCE1="COMPREHENSIVE1"><DATE VALUE="1679-05-">May 1679</DATE><CHRONPROSE>When LLH was about ten and her <NAME STANDARD="Powis, William Herbert,,, first Duke of">father</NAME> was imprisoned in the Tower of London, the home of her family in <PLACE><PLACENAME>Lincoln&apos;s Inn Fields</PLACENAME>, <SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, was broken into at midnight by an armed mob.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (c.1626-1696)" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>This rampaging crowd of anti-Catholics were on the hunt for alleged traitors.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></VIOLENCE></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="MOTHER"><DIV2><HEADING>Mother</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>Lady Lucy&apos;s mother, <NAME STANDARD="Powis, Elizabeth Herbert,,, Duchess of">Elizabeth Herbert, Baroness and eventually Duchess of Powis</NAME>, was born into the highest ranks of Catholic monarchists and through her father (<NAME STANDARD="Worcester, Edward Somerset,,, second Marquess of">Edward Somerset, second Marquess of Worcester</NAME>, soldier, diplomat, and scientist) was a great-grand-daughter of <NAME STANDARD="Russell, Elizabeth,,, Lady">Elizabeth Russell</NAME>. Elizabeth, one of the famously learned Cook sisters, in 1605 published a translation on a topic not unlike that of LLH&apos;s own first publication: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Way of Reconciliation of a Good and Learned Man, A">A Way of Reconciliation . . . Touching the <SIC>Trueth</SIC>, Nature, and Substance of the Body and Blood of Christ in the Sacrament </TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (c.1626-1696) and Edward Somerset" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>Lady Powis (as she was until 1689)<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> used her rank to help her fellow Catholics: for instance, she <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="patron">served as patron</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> to the midwife <NAME>Elizabeth Cellier</NAME>, commissioning her for a kind of survey of Catholics in prison and later seeking royal support for Cellier&apos;s scheme for a professional society for midwives. Lady Powis also (according to <NAME>Victor Stater</NAME> in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Oxford Dictionary of National Biography">ODNB</TITLE>) <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="political conspirator">conspired</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> with Cellier to spread rumours of a <SOCALLED>Presbyterian Plot</SOCALLED>, a mirror image of the alleged Popish Plot in connection with which which her husband had already been arrested. The public proved more sceptical about Protestant than Catholic plotting. <NAME>Thomas Dangerfield</NAME>, who was apparently working for Lady Powis, proved a double agent, and Lady Powis was accused of treason (in a third fictitious plot, that of the <SOCALLED>Meal Tub</SOCALLED> where incriminating papers were planted). She <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="writer">wrote and published at least one, though probably two, ballads</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> about the plots.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696) and Elizabeth Cellier)" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="NATIONALINTERNATIONAL" RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN1="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS1" RELEVANCE1="COMPREHENSIVE1"><DATERANGE FROM="1679-11-04" TO="1680-02-12" EXACT="BOTH">4 November 1679 to 12 February 1680</DATERANGE><CHRONPROSE><NAME STANDARD="Powis, Elizabeth Herbert,,, Duchess of">Lady Powis</NAME>, mother of two future writers (<NAME STANDARD="Herbert, Lady Lucy">Lucy</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Nithsdale, Winifred Maxwell,,, Countess of">Winifred</NAME>, then about ten and seven), joined her <NAME STANDARD="Powis, William Herbert,,, first Duke of">husband</NAME> in the <PLACE><PLACENAME>Tower of London</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, on a charge of Roman Catholic plotting against the life of <NAME STANDARD="Charles II, King">Charles II</NAME>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>This was the outcome of the <SOCALLED>Meal Tub Plot</SOCALLED>, so called after the container in <NAME>Elizabeth Cellier</NAME>&apos;s kitchen where evidence was planted. Lady Powis was then granted bail, and the charges against her were dropped. Under <NAME STANDARD="James II, King">James II</NAME>, by contrast, she not only rose with her husband in the scale of the nobility, but served as a <JOB>courtier</JOB> to <NAME STANDARD="Mary of Modena,, Queen of England">Mary of Modena</NAME> and in <DATE VALUE="1688-06-10" CERTAINTY="AFTER">June 1688</DATE> was appointed <SOCALLED>governess</SOCALLED> to the newborn <NAME STANDARD="Stuart, James Edward">Prince of Wales</NAME>. Her actions were crucial to this baby in two ways: she testified to his legitimacy and she was instrumental in getting him off <SOCALLED>pap</SOCALLED> (a concoction of cow&apos;s milk and gluten) and onto human milk.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Tayler 7-8" DBREF="70086">7-8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> In this capacity, she followed her royal mistress into exile and she was still the prince&apos;s <JOB>governess</JOB> when she died on <DATE>11 March 1691</DATE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER><MEMBER RELATION="FATHER"><DIV2><HEADING>Father</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>Lucy&apos;s father, <NAME STANDARD="Powis, William Herbert,,, first Duke of">William Herbert</NAME>, <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="landowner">owned estates</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> in Wales and the Welsh marches, although much of the family&apos;s large properties had been forfeited after they fought for the monarchy in the <TOPIC>English Civil War</TOPIC>. He was Baron of Powis at the time of Lucy&apos;s birth and was made an earl six years later: one of the highest-ranking <ORGNAME STANDARD="Roman Catholic Church">Catholic</ORGNAME> peers. When <NAME>Titus Oates</NAME> fomented national panic over an alleged <SOCALLED>Popish Plot</SOCALLED> to murder <NAME STANDARD="Charles II, King">Charles II</NAME> and forcibly Catholicize the country, Powis was <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="politician">said to have been chosen to assume the post of Lord Treasurer after the revolution</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>. He was arrested and spent five and a half years in the <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="Tower of London">Tower</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, from October 1678 to February 1684, when he was released on bail (provided by Protestant as well as Catholic peers). He <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="writer">published a pamphlet</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> about the plot during his imprisonment in 1679.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><NAME STANDARD="James II, King">James II</NAME> rewarded him with the title of marquess (in March 1687) and gave him various official positions (with a dispensation from the Test Act which normally barred Catholics from holding them). Among James&apos;s ideologically extremist circle Powis was a moderate. He went into exile with his king in December 1688 and was rewarded early the next year with a Jacobite dukedom. He <JOB REG="army officer">accompanied James in invading</JOB> Ireland in 1690 and remained <JOB REG="courtier">prominent at his court</JOB>. He died on <DATE>12 July 1696</DATE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER><MEMBER RELATION="SISTER"><DIV2><HEADING>Sisters</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>LLH&apos;s younger sister, <NAME STANDARD="Nithsdale, Winifred Maxwell,,, Countess of">Winifred, later Lady Nithsdale</NAME>, acquired a reputation as a heroine by successfully carrying through a daring plan to spring her husband from his captivity in the <PLACE><PLACENAME>Tower of London</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> the very night before he was to have been executed.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Winifred Maxwell" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>Of her other sisters, Frances became by marriage <NAME STANDARD="Seaforth, Frances Mackenzie,,, Countess of">Countess of Seaforth</NAME> and Anne became <NAME STANDARD="Carrington, Anne,,, Viscountess">Viscountess Carrington</NAME>. Their sister <NAME STANDARD="Maxwell, Mary,,, Lady">Mary</NAME> was three times married: her second husband was Francis Browne, fourth Viscount Montagu, and her third was Sir George Maxwell, a baronet.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Durrant 324ff" DBREF="17072">324ff</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER><MEMBER RELATION="BROTHER"><DIV2><HEADING>Brother, Niece</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>LLH&apos;s eldest brother, another William Herbert, succeeded to their father&apos;s titles, but since those titles were attainted for treason he <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">remained legally a commoner until 1722.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (1657x61-1745)" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> He was an active <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>Jacobite</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>, an <JOB REG="army officer">army officer</JOB>, and a <JOB>spy</JOB> using a range of aliases, who lived sometimes abroad and sometimes in Britain. He spent six months in the <PLACE><PLACENAME CURRENT="Tower of London">Tower of London</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> in 1689, another six in <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="Newgate Prison">Newgate</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> in 1696-7, and eight in the Tower from September 1715 to May 1716. He managed to <JOB REG="landowner">repossess most of the family estates</JOB>, but was never free from debt and money troubles until his death in 1745.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (1657x61-1745)" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER><MEMBER RELATION="NIECE"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>His eldest child, <NAME>Lady Mary Herbert</NAME>, became notorious as an early stock-exchange <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>market speculator</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>, who acquired fabulous wealth but then lost it all again. Her later notoriety was as an international <JOB>mining entrepreneur</JOB>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (1657x61-1745)" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><VIOLENCE><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN1="NATIONALINTERNATIONAL1" RELEVANCE1="COMPREHENSIVE1"><DATE VALUE="1684-10-">October 1684</DATE><CHRONPROSE>The <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="Lincoln&apos;s Inn Fields">Lincoln&apos;s Inn Fields</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> house of <NAME STANDARD="Powis, William Herbert,,, first Duke of">Lord Powis</NAME> (recently released after years in prison on suspicion of treasonable <ORGNAME STANDARD="Roman Catholic Church">Catholic</ORGNAME> plotting, father of future writers <NAME STANDARD="Herbert, Lady Lucy">Lucy</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Nithsdale, Winifred Maxwell,,, Countess of">Winifred</NAME>) was burned to the ground by chance or malice.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>A sectarian motive was assumed. Two page-boys were said to have died in the flames, and the family was lucky to get out alive. Permission to rebuild was granted by <NAME STANDARD="James II, King">James II</NAME> in June 1685. The house was attacked again in the month that its master fled with James from the country.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696)" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></VIOLENCE></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Education</HEADING><EDUCATION MODE="DOMESTIC"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Though the upbringing of LLH was marked by instability and violence, she somehow acquired a good education for her time and gender. If she indeed wrote confident pronouncements later in life about <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">right education</QUOTE> as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">practised by them yt understood perfectly ye educating of youth,</QUOTE> it seems that she felt she had had the best.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Durrant 430" DBREF="17072" QTDIN="QTDINYES">430</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></EDUCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Exile</HEADING><LOCATION RELATIONTO="MIGRATED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>When <NAME STANDARD="James II, King">James II</NAME> fled from his <PLACE><GEOG REG="England">kingdom</GEOG></PLACE> at the end of 1688, LLH&apos;s parents accompanied him into <PLACE><GEOG>France</GEOG> to his court at <SETTLEMENT REG="St-Germain-en-Laye">St Germain</SETTLEMENT></PLACE>. They sent for her at some time over the next couple of years. Soon after that, in pursuit of her religious vocation, LLH settled at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Bruges</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Belgium"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 17, 19" DBREF="70285">17, 19</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><WEALTH><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Most of the remaining Powis family estates, valued at &pound;10,000 a year, were re-assigned to Whigs by <NAME STANDARD="William III, King">William III</NAME> after 1688. It took LLH&apos;s relations years of struggle to recoup some of them.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under William Herbert (c. 1626-1696) and William Herbert (1657x61-1745)" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></WEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><OCCUPATION><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>While at <PLACE><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG><SETTLEMENT REG="St-Germain-en-Laye">St Germain</SETTLEMENT></PLACE>, LLH attended the court of <NAME STANDARD="Mary of Modena,, Queen of England">Mary Beatrice of Modena</NAME>, but it does not appear that she held any official position there as her mother and sister did.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 21" DBREF="70285">21</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>The Convent</HEADING><LOCATION RELATIONTO="TRAVELLED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>After she took the decision to enter the religious life, LLH spent some time travelling around <PLACE><GEOG>France</GEOG></PLACE> visiting various English convents. She also studied their various Rules.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Lady Lucy Herbert" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Durrant 309" DBREF="17072">309</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> (Since religious orders were forbidden in Britain, many communities of Englishwomen flourished abroad).</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><OCCUPATION><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG"><DATE VALUE="1692-03-01">1 March 1692</DATE><CHRONPROSE>The year after her <NAME STANDARD="Powis, Elizabeth Herbert,,, Duchess of">mother</NAME>&apos;s death, LLH was <JOB CURRENTALTERNATIVETERM="novice nun" REG="nun"><SOCALLED>clothed</SOCALLED></JOB> at the convent of the <ORGNAME REG="English Canonesses Regular of St Augustine " STANDARD="English Augustinian Canonesses">English Augustinian Canonesses</ORGNAME>: <PLACE><PLACENAME>Nazareth Monastery</PLACENAME> (called the <SOCALLED>English Convent</SOCALLED>) at <SETTLEMENT>Bruges</SETTLEMENT><GEOG CURRENT="Belgium" REG="Belgium"></GEOG></PLACE>, where she took the name <NAME STANDARD="Herbert, Lady Lucy">Sister Teresa Joseph</NAME>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Durrant 311" DBREF="17072">311</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Lady Lucy Herbert" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>She liked the Bruges convent because she had no friends or relations there and because she approved the simplicity of its way of life. Her family disliked the idea of her becoming a nun, and would have preferred a convent in France, as more accessible for visiting.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Lady Lucy Herbert" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Durrant 309" DBREF="17072">309</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The one she chose at Bruges was the convent where the autobiographer <NAME>Catherine Holland</NAME>, a generation older than LLH, was still living. Herbert so impressed her superiors that she was, unusually, allowed to take the habit of a novice only two weeks after entering the convent.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Durrant 315" DBREF="17072">315</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG"><DATE VALUE="1693-06-01">1 June 1693</DATE><CHRONPROSE>LLH (Sister Teresa Joseph) made her profession as a <JOB REG="nun">nun</JOB> at the <ORGNAME REG="English Canonesses Regular of St Augustine " STANDARD="English Augustinian Canonesses">English Augustinian</ORGNAME> convent at <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="Nazareth Monastery"></PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT>Bruges</SETTLEMENT><GEOG CURRENT="Belgium" REG="Belgium"></GEOG></PLACE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Durrant 316" DBREF="17072">316</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Lady Lucy Herbert" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>She had made her vows privately in March, on the Feast of the Annunciation. She was elected Procuratrix (an important post on the practical, managerial, financial side of the convent) in <DATE>1696</DATE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Durrant 316" DBREF="17072">316</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG"><DATE VALUE="1709-03-05">5 March 1709</DATE><CHRONPROSE>LLH was elected <JOB CURRENTALTERNATIVETERM="prioress" REG="nun">Prioress or Mother Superior</JOB> of her convent, that of the <ORGNAME REG="English Canonesses Regular of St Augustine " STANDARD="English Augustinian Canonesses">English Augustinians</ORGNAME> at <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="Nazareth Monastery"></PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT>Bruges</SETTLEMENT><GEOG CURRENT="Belgium" REG="Belgium"></GEOG></PLACE>; she thus became Mother Teresa Joseph.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Lady Lucy Herbert" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>Under her rule the community grew in numbers, celebrated its centenary in 1729 (with two barrels of beer for the neighbours as well as two hundred loaves of bread given to the poor), rebuilt its church (with the addition in 1738 of a marble altar imported from Rome), and put up a new house for its chaplain. On the fiftieth anniversary of Mother Teresa Joseph&apos;s profession (during the last year of her life) the convent received gifts from far and wide, including a number of items from <NAME STANDARD="Nithsdale, Winifred Maxwell,,, Countess of">Lady Nithsdale</NAME> at Rome.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Durrant 326-8" DBREF="17072">326-8</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Lady Lucy Herbert" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The account of Mother Teresa Joseph in the convent Chronicle mentions on the one hand <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">her meekness and sweetness of temper</QUOTE> and on the other her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">heroic courage to overcome all difficulties in everything she undertook for the glory of God.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Durrant 328" DBREF="17072" QTDIN="QTDINYES">328</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><POLITICS><DIV2><HEADING>Political Activity</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>LLH, like her parents, was a <POLITICALAFFILIATION ACTIVISM="ACTIVISTYES" REG="Jacobite">Jacobite</POLITICALAFFILIATION> and an activist in the cause. She looked on <NAME>James Edward Stuart</NAME> as James III, rightful king of England and Scotland, and must have been delighted when he visited her convent on <DATE>8 August 1708</DATE>. It seems that she associated herself with the novelist <NAME>Jane Barker</NAME> in a campaign to get his father, <NAME STANDARD="James II, King">James II</NAME>, canonized as a saint.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Durrant 316-7" DBREF="17072">316-7</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="King xiv, 103-5 and notes" DBREF="8928">xiv, 103-5 and notes</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></POLITICS></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="SISTER"><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="IMG"><DATE VALUE="1716-08-12">12 August 1716</DATE><CHRONPROSE>Mother Teresa Joseph (LLH) was visited at her <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="Nazareth Monastery"></PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT>Bruges</SETTLEMENT><GEOG CURRENT="Belgium" REG="Belgium"></GEOG></PLACE> <ORGNAME REG="English Canonesses Regular of St Augustine " STANDARD="English Augustinian Canonesses">convent</ORGNAME> by her sister <NAME STANDARD="Nithsdale, Winifred Maxwell,,, Countess of">Lady Nithsdale</NAME>, in shaken health after her successful rescue of her <NAME STANDARD="Nithsdale, William Maxwell,,, fifth Earl of">husband</NAME> from the Tower of London and her gruelling efforts before and after it.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McArthur 117" DBREF="70125">117</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 95-6" DBREF="70285">95-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>The two sisters had not seen each other for twenty-four years. Winifred stayed until 14 September.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maxwell Stuart 96" DBREF="70285">96</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McArthur 117" DBREF="70125">117</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>Another sister, <NAME STANDARD="Maxwell, Mary,,, Lady">Mary, Lady Maxwell (formerly Montagu)</NAME>, entered the same convent in 1739 <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">with the design to end her days among us.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Durrant 324" DBREF="17072">324</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><POLITICS><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>It was LLH who persuaded her sister <NAME STANDARD="Nithsdale, Winifred Maxwell,,, Countess of">Winifred</NAME> to write out the full story of how she engineered her husband&apos;s escape from the <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="Tower of London">Tower</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> and who then preserved and apparently circulated the story. She no doubt <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">understood the importance of her sister&apos;s account to Catholic recusant history.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McArthur 117" DBREF="70125">117</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Nuns were accustomed to both writing and reading vivid accounts not only of their enclosed female communities but also of the struggles of women in the world to preserve the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Roman Catholic Church">Catholic</ORGNAME> faith under persecution (often while their husbands were in prison). Scholar <NAME>Isobel Grundy</NAME> has suggested that in playing midwife to her sister&apos;s writing, LLH was helping to bring <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the convent historical tradition to the eyes of a secular readership.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Grundy, Women&apos;s History? 138" DBREF="5610">138</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McArthur 117" DBREF="70125">117</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></POLITICS></DIV1><DIV1><FRIENDSASSOCIATES><DIV2><HEADING>Nuns and Laywomen</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>Though she had chosen to distance herself from family and friends in entering the convent, LLH was much beloved by her sisters, and later her daughters, in religion. When she was close to death, she asked, as the convent chronicler related, that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">she might be left alone as much as possible the remaining time she was in the world, but that being too hard a task for her children . . . she cheerfully submitted to our going to her as often as we could.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Durrant 328-9" DBREF="17072" QTDIN="QTDINYES">328-9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>LLH met the novelist <NAME>Jane Barker</NAME> before she became a nun, and after entering the convent she became acquainted with the autobiographer <NAME>Catherine Holland</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Latz 38" DBREF="13258">38</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She was visited at her convent late in life by the diarist and letter-writer <NAME STANDARD="Pomfret, Henrietta Louisa Fermor,,, Countess of">Lady Pomfret</NAME>, who had been given an introduction by her sister Lady Nithsdale in Italy in spring 1741.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Lady Charlotte Finch, unpublished diary" DBREF="70045"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FRIENDSASSOCIATES></DIV1><DIV1><HEALTH ISSUE="PHYSICAL"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>She had two years of increasingly frail health before she died, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">but could by no means be persuaded to stay from the choir and refectory</QUOTE> until compelled to do so by her superior priest.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Durrant 328" DBREF="17072">328</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></HEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Death</HEADING><DEATH><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="SYS"><DATE VALUE="1744-01-19">19 January 1744</DATE><CHRONPROSE>Mother Teresa Joseph (LLH) died at her convent, that of the <ORGNAME REG="English Canonesses Regular of St Augustine " STANDARD="English Augustinian Canonesses">English Augustinians</ORGNAME> at <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="Nazareth Monastery"></PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT>Bruges</SETTLEMENT><GEOG CURRENT="Belgium" REG="Belgium"></GEOG></PLACE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Lady Lucy Herbert" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>She was buried on the 23rd, probably though not certainly at the convent.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="ODNB under Lady Lucy Herbert" DBREF="29268"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></DEATH></DIV1><WORKSCITED><SOURCE>Unless otherwise noted, all information is from the FC.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Durrant, Catherine S. A Link between Flemish Mystics and English Martyrs.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Finch, Lady Charlotte. MS diary.<RESEARCHNOTE>uncheckable</RESEARCHNOTE></SOURCE><SOURCE>Isobel Grundy, &quot;Women&apos;s History&quot; in Grundy and Wiseman, eds. Women, Writing, History.</SOURCE><SOURCE>King, Kathryn.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Latz, Dorothy L. Neglected.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Maxwell Stuart, Flora. Lady Nithsdale and the Jacobites. 1995.</SOURCE><SOURCE>McArthur, Tonya Moutray. &quot;Through the Grate&quot; in The Catholic Church and Unruly Women Writers.</SOURCE><SOURCE>ODNB</SOURCE><SOURCE>Henrietta Tayler, Lady Nithsdale and her Family. 1939.</SOURCE></WORKSCITED></DIV0></BIOGRAPHY>